{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_u0nqoLeKlvzFXLZsMlSine1E","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Run, judge, and FIX `{{SCENARIO_ID}}` — one failure per invocation\n2\t\n3\tYou drive `{{SCENARIO_DIR}}/scenario.yaml` against a LOCAL `lmthing serve`, judge each step on real\n4\tevidence, and when a step fails you fix it at the right layer and PROVE the fix with a fresh rerun.\n5\tYou do this for the FIRST failure only, then stop. You **never commit** — you leave your changes\n6\tuncommitted and write a full report explaining every one; a human reviews and commits to `main`.\n7\t\n8\t{{include:scenario-spec.md}}\n9\t\n10\t# How to run the scenario (the exact commands)\n11\t\n12\tEverything runs LOCAL against a throwaway `lmthing serve` (budget-free Azure keys from\n13\t`sdk/org/.env`); there is no CI / image / kubectl / ArgoCD. From the monorepo root:\n14\t\n15\t1. **Build once** (and again after any code fix): `cd sdk/org && pnpm --filter @lmthing/cli... build`.\n16\t2. **Launch the replay in the BACKGROUND.** The full run is 30–40 min — longer than the 10-min\n17\t   Bash-tool cap — so it CANNOT be one foreground call. The runner wipes the pod runtime root (and\n18\t   prints `confirmed: fresh pod has 0 projects`), starts a clean server, provisions the one project,\n19\t   writes its own `$ART/runner.pid` (so `kill $(cat \"$ART/runner.pid\")` is always correct — you never\n20\t   improvise the stop), and writes `step-NN.json` + appends `trace.md` after EACH step:\n21\t\n22\t       ART=<ARTIFACT_DIR>   # the dir holding {{progressFile}}; evidence + your report live here\n23\t       # ABSOLUTE path to the runner — it must not depend on your current directory (its own imports\n24\t       # and the pod's cwd are script-relative, so it runs correctly from anywhere):\n25\t       SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node {{repoRoot}}/sdk/org/scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n26\t         --fresh-server --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n27\t\n28\t3. **Immediately POLL — and DO NOT END YOUR TURN.** ⚠️ THE #1 FAILURE MODE: launching the runner,\n29\t   sending a message like \"I'll evaluate step-01 when it lands\", and stopping. A headless session\n30\t   ENDS the instant you stop emitting tool calls — the run then dies UNJUDGED and the whole\n31\t   invocation is wasted. Your turn ends ONLY after you have judged through the first failing step\n32\t   (and fixed + verified it) or confirmed the scenario fully green. To stay alive AND advance, run\n33\t   this BLOCKING poll as a tool call (set the Bash `timeout` to its max, 600000 ms) with `S` = the\n34\t   next step to judge; it returns the moment that step's evidence lands or the runner ends:\n35\t\n36\t       S=01; F=\"$ART/step-$S.json\"\n37\t       for i in $(seq 1 96); do\n38\t         [ -f \"$F\" ] && { echo \"STEP $S READY:\"; cat \"$F\"; exit 0; }\n39\t         # Runner ended? clean finish (played N/N), OR a CRASH (module/load error, or its pid died).\n40\t         if grep -qE \"played [0-9]+/[0-9]+ steps|run-yaml:|Cannot find module|MODULE_NOT_FOUND|node:internal/modules\" \"$ART/run.log\" 2>/dev/null \\\n41\t            || { [ -f \"$ART/runner.pid\" ] && ! kill -0 \"$(cat \"$ART/runner.pid\")\" 2>/dev/null; }; then\n42\t           echo \"RUNNER ENDED before step $S (finished or CRASHED — READ the log, don't re-poll blindly):\"\n43\t           tail -15 \"$ART/run.log\"; exit 0\n44\t         fi\n45\t         sleep 5\n46\t       done\n47\t       echo \"still waiting for step $S (~8m) — RUN THE POLL AGAIN, do not stop\"\n48\t\n49\t   Read the returned `step-NN.json` (delegates / yields / errors / reply, the asks, and the real\n50\t   spaces + app tables + DB rows), JUDGE it against that step's `expect` + the invariants, then poll\n51\t   the NEXT step (`S=02`, `S=03`, …). Each poll blocks ≤ ~8 min, safely under the cap; if it prints\n52\t   \"still waiting\", run it again. `trace.md` carries the same evidence in prose with the checklist.\n53\t4. **At the FIRST failing step, STOP the runner** — `kill $(cat \"$ART/runner.pid\") 2>/dev/null` — and\n54\t   go to attribute + fix (below). Do NOT wait for later steps; your fix changes the state they'd run\n55\t   on. If a poll returns `RUNNER ENDED … played 18/18`, every step passed → the scenario is fully\n56\t   green → extend.\n57\t5. **Verify-rerun** (after a fix): rebuild if you touched code (`pnpm --filter @lmthing/core... build`\n58\t   for a system-space/core fix — the fresh server adopts the rebuilt `dist/system-spaces` on boot),\n59\t   then relaunch the SAME background+poll but only THROUGH the failed step:\n60\t\n61\t       SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node {{repoRoot}}/sdk/org/scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n62\t         --fresh-server --through <N> --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n63\t\n64\t   Poll `S=<N>`, confirm it (and every earlier step) now passes, then stop. `--plan` dry-prints the\n65\t   steps without a pod.\n66\t\n67\t# The persona is played FOR you — you REVIEW the asks, you don't type them\n68\t\n69\tThe runner plays the persona: it sends each step's message(s) and answers THING's asks from the\n70\tstep's `if_asked` map and the scenario `knows` list (consent is approved unless a step sets\n71\t`deny_consent`). Every ask + how it was answered is recorded in the step evidence, so you do NOT type\n72\tanswers turn-by-turn — you REVIEW the recorded asks and SCORE them (below). When the runner logs an\n73\tUNANSWERED ask (no `if_asked` match), decide which it is:\n74\t- a legitimate question the scenario simply didn't ground → add an `if_asked` entry (an **L0**\n75\t  scenario fix) and rerun;\n76\t- an over-ask THING should never have made → an **L1** failure (fix its brain toward \"propose and\n77\t  act; only ask when the choice is truly the user's\").\n78\t\n79\t# Judge a step — evidence, not vibes\n80\t\n81\tPASS only when every `expect` and every touched invariant is confirmed on the trace or on disk —\n82\tstate where you looked (the delegate path, the yield, the DB row, the knowledge file and its `source`\n83\tline). A reply that SOUNDS right but left no trace / state is a FAIL. Separate RECOVERED errors (the\n84\tloop retried, the deliverable still landed → a metric) from FATAL ones (the deliverable never landed\n85\t→ fail).\n86\t\n87\t**Score the ask itself.** An `ask()` is behavior, so it can satisfy OR violate an invariant (see\n88\t\"Asking well\"): a legitimate clarification / consent is a PASS — and where an invariant REQUIRES it\n89\t(ambiguous \"don't forget\" → save-vs-remind; an equal-precedence conflict → ask), NOT asking is the\n90\tFAIL. An over-ask — interrogating instead of proposing / researching / querying, or re-asking what's\n91\talready known — is a FAIL at L1.\n92\t\n93\t# The loop — ONE failure per invocation\n94\t\n95\tRun from step 1. Then exactly one of:\n96\t\n97\t**A. A step FAILS** → stop the run at that step (the rest would run on corrupted state). Then:\n98\t  1. **Attribute before you touch anything.** FIRST `git diff` the file you would fix — a prior\n99\t     invocation may have left an UNCOMMITTED change already addressing this exact behavior. If the\n100\t     instruction ALREADY says the right thing (e.g. \"each distinct part gets its own specialist,\n101\t     brevity is not a merge\") and the step STILL fails the same way, L1 is exhausted — do NOT add a\n102\t     fourth sentence saying the same thing louder. That standing-but-ineffective prose is proof the\n103\t     cause is structural: CLIMB (see the L2 note below). Then re-run the failing turn as a minimal\n104\t     one-shot probe on a clean project, to place it on the ladder:\n105\t     - Same ask phrased DIRECTLY authors cleanly, but the in-persona phrasing didn't → **L1** (the\n106\t       brain judged / routed badly).\n107\t     - The agent tried the right thing but a call THREW or failed TYPECHECK → the primitive is\n108\t       missing / too weak → **L2 or L3**, never a prompt.\n109\t     - The `expect` was wrong or the message truly ambiguous → **L0**. Do not weaken a real assertion\n110\t       to go green.\n111\t     - **A clean direct probe does NOT prove L1.** \"The primitive can do it when asked directly\" only\n112\t       rules out L2/L3 for a *one-shot capability* failure. It does NOT rule out L2 when the real-path\n113\t       behavior is UNRELIABLE or SYSTEMATICALLY wrong: L2 is not only \"the primitive is missing,\" it is\n114\t       also \"the current STRUCTURE doesn't reliably drive the primitive.\" If the same step fails the\n115\t       same way across two independent replays — and especially if it drops the SAME items each time\n116\t       (systematic, not random) — a third prose tweak will not fix it. That repetition is the ladder\n117\t       telling you to CLIMB. Before you touch prose again, TRACE two things: (a) WHERE the wrong\n118\t       decision is actually made (the caller's payload, or the specialist's own design node?), and\n119\t       (b) WHAT INPUT it saw (a decision made on a lossy summary that never contained the dropped\n120\t       items is fixed by changing the INPUT or adding an enumeration STEP, never by exhorting the\n121\t       agent to try harder). A free-form judgment that must come out the same every time wants a\n122\t       DETERMINISTIC structure — an enumerate-then-`forEach` tasklist node that lists the parts as\n123\t       discrete items and builds one per item — which is an **L2** artifact that does not exist yet.\n124\t  2. **Fix at the LOWEST rung that truly fixes it** (ladder below). Land it in SOURCE, rebuild,\n125\t     restart the local server so the tree is adopted.\n126\t  3. **Verify with a fresh rerun.** New directory / project / DB / spaces, from step 1, forward\n127\t     THROUGH the previously-failed step. The moment that step (and everything before it) passes,\n128\t     STOP — do not go on to later steps; that is the next invocation's job. A from-scratch replay is\n129\t     the only thing that proves a shared `instruct.md` change didn't regress an earlier step.\n130\t  4. **If the fix does not verify:** revise and rerun a COUPLE more times (≈2–3 total). If that step\n131\t     still won't go green, STOP and report the still-failing state honestly — do not grind your\n132\t     context to dust chasing it. A later invocation, with fresh context, tries again.\n133\t\n134\t**B. Every step PASSES (no failure)** → the scenario is fully green → **author ONE extension** to it\n135\t  per `extend.md` (add steps reaching an untouched capability, same persona), and STOP. Do NOT run\n136\t  the new steps this invocation — the next invocation runs them.\n137\t\n138\t# The fix ladder — take the lowest rung; prove you can't stay lower\n139\t\n140\t**L0 SCENARIO** — the assertion / message was wrong. Fix `scenario.yaml`. Guard: you are not lowering\n141\ta bar the product actually failed.\n142\t\n143\t**L1 PROMPT** — the artifact exists, it just decided / said the wrong thing (most failures). Name\n144\tWHICH: agent `instruct.md` (act vs answer vs delegate vs refuse; three-store routing; research vs\n145\tquery) · `charter.md` (fork-safe guardrail) · a tasklist task `NN-<id>.md` (its INSTRUCTION, or its\n146\tFRONTMATTER: `role` / `functions` / `canDelegateTo` / `capabilities` / `output` / `dependsOn` /\n147\t`forEach` / `condition` — never forbid a tool in prose, gate it in frontmatter) · a tasklist\n148\t`index.md` · `knowledge/<domain>/<field>/<option>.md` · a space function's body. Fix as a GENERAL\n149\tPRINCIPLE a competent colleague would agree with; ZERO scenario literals (persona name, fixture\n150\tcontents, this scenario's table names — in instruction OR example) — that is overfitting and fails.\n151\t**And ZERO scenario-DOMAIN framing** — a grep for literals won't catch it, but a travel scenario's fix\n152\tthat reasons about \"itineraries\" / \"destinations\", a cooking one about \"recipes\" / \"ingredients\", a\n153\tclinic one about \"patients\", is overfit just the same: it bends a system-wide brain toward this one\n154\tstory's domain. Write the domain-NEUTRAL principle (the failure here — merging a small part into a\n155\tcatch-all — generalizes as \"brevity is not a reason to merge; a distinct part with few facts still gets\n156\tits own specialist\"). Before you land an L1 edit, ask: could this exact sentence have come from a\n157\tscenario in a completely different domain? If not, rewrite it until it could.\n158\t\n159\t**L2 STRUCTURE MISSING** — expressible today, but the artifact doesn't exist. Add it, inside the\n160\tspace format (no core change): a new AGENT · a new TASKLIST or TASK NODE · a new SPACE FUNCTION · a\n161\tnew capability grant or `canDelegateTo` edge on an existing agent.\n162\t\n163\t**L3 FRAMEWORK GAP** — today's primitives CANNOT express it, and you can point at where a lower rung\n164\twould go and show it has no way to say the thing. A core change (`sdk/org/libs/core|cli/**`), held to\n165\tthe runtime discipline:\n166\t- a new or improved FRONTMATTER FIELD on an agent / task, when no field says it; OR\n167\t- a new GLOBAL + capability + DTS + injection + fork-intersection, when the model surface lacks the\n168\t  power; OR\n169\t- a change to the turn loop / fork / tasklist orchestrator / typecheck.\n170\tShips LOCKSTEP (not-granted ⇒ not-injected ⇒ absent from the DTS ⇒ a clean typecheck error), WITH a\n171\ttest that would have caught the gap, and the matching `org/docs/` page updated in the SAME change\n172\t(`pnpm docs:check` is a hard gate). L3 is heavy and it is the judge's most dangerous power — enter it\n173\tonly on proof, and flag it loudest of all in the report so the human reviewing knows a framework\n174\tchange is in the diff.\n175\t\n176\t> The routing rebuild is the worked example that needs all three: THING misrouting where data lived\n177\t> took L1 (the three-store triage rewrite), L2 (the `write_fact` / `retract_fact` / `reconcile_conflict`\n178\t> / `answer_across_spaces` / `migrate_to_app_db` tasklists + DB grants), and L3 (`writeKnowledge`, the\n179\t> `knowledge:write` capability, the per-task `capabilities:` field). A judge that only ever reached\n180\t> for L1 would have kept polishing prose while the real gap was a missing primitive.\n181\t\n182\t# You NEVER commit — you report, a human commits\n183\t\n184\tLeave every change UNCOMMITTED in the working tree (system-space files, and for L3 the core + test +\n185\tdoc). Do not `git add`, `git commit`, `git stash`, or switch branches. Your report is the interface\n186\tto the human who reviews the diff and commits to `main` — it must be good enough that they can review\n187\ta core change without re-deriving the failure.\n188\t\n189\t## The report (write it as `report.md` in the same directory as your progress log `{{progressFile}}`)\n190\t\n191\tThere is NO per-scenario `results/` dir and NO `run.mjs` — a scenario is just `scenario.yaml` +\n192\t`fixtures/`, played by the generic runner. Your report lives beside `{{progressFile}}` in the round's\n193\tartifact tree, which the engine commits with its ledger; the PRODUCT diff it describes stays\n194\tuncommitted for the human.\n195\t- **Verdict** for this invocation: which step failed (or \"fully green → extended\"), and whether the\n196\t  fix verified.\n197\t- **Per change:** the file + symbol you changed; the RUNG (L0–L3) and WHY, with the probe that proved\n198\t  attribution; the GENERAL PRINCIPLE behind an L1 fix; the before → after behavior with the trace\n199\t  that proves it; and for L3, the test you added and the doc you updated. Grep-confirm no scenario\n200\t  literal entered any agent's brain.\n201\t- **Evidence:** the failing trace excerpt (the exact `eval_error` / `typecheck_error` statement, the\n202\t  delegate path, the yields, the rows / knowledge files), and the verifying rerun's trace.\n203\t- **If unfixed:** the still-failing state, honestly, with what you tried and why you stopped. An\n204\t  honest FAIL you couldn't fix without overfitting beats a fake PASS.\n205\t\n206\t## Done\n207\tThe failing step is fixed and verified by a fresh rerun (or honestly reported as still-failing after\n208\ta couple of tries), OR the fully-green scenario has been extended by one batch — and the report\n209\texplains every change. Everything is UNCOMMITTED, ready for human review + commit to `main`.\n210\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b8a0991b-bce4-420b-844a-664f990ff54b","uuid":"8a9052ee-da58-4c7c-a23c-8c0b6699fa69","timestamp":"2026-07-15T22:38:21.710Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/automation/instances/scenario-campaign/judge.md","content":"# Run, judge, and FIX `{{SCENARIO_ID}}` — one failure per invocation\n\nYou drive `{{SCENARIO_DIR}}/scenario.yaml` against a LOCAL `lmthing serve`, judge each step on real\nevidence, and when a step fails you fix it at the right layer and PROVE the fix with a fresh rerun.\nYou do this for the FIRST failure only, then stop. You **never commit** — you leave your changes\nuncommitted and write a full report explaining every one; a human reviews and commits to `main`.\n\n{{include:scenario-spec.md}}\n\n# How to run the scenario (the exact commands)\n\nEverything runs LOCAL against a throwaway `lmthing serve` (budget-free Azure keys from\n`sdk/org/.env`); there is no CI / image / kubectl / ArgoCD. From the monorepo root:\n\n1. **Build once** (and again after any code fix): `cd sdk/org && pnpm --filter @lmthing/cli... build`.\n2. **Launch the replay in the BACKGROUND.** The full run is 30–40 min — longer than the 10-min\n   Bash-tool cap — so it CANNOT be one foreground call. The runner wipes the pod runtime root (and\n   prints `confirmed: fresh pod has 0 projects`), starts a clean server, provisions the one project,\n   writes its own `$ART/runner.pid` (so `kill $(cat \"$ART/runner.pid\")` is always correct — you never\n   improvise the stop), and writes `step-NN.json` + appends `trace.md` after EACH step:\n\n       ART=<ARTIFACT_DIR>   # the dir holding {{progressFile}}; evidence + your report live here\n       # ABSOLUTE path to the runner — it must not depend on your current directory (its own imports\n       # and the pod's cwd are script-relative, so it runs correctly from anywhere):\n       SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node {{repoRoot}}/sdk/org/scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n         --fresh-server --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n\n3. **Immediately POLL — and DO NOT END YOUR TURN.** ⚠️ THE #1 FAILURE MODE: launching the runner,\n   sending a message like \"I'll evaluate step-01 when it lands\", and stopping. A headless session\n   ENDS the instant you stop emitting tool calls — the run then dies UNJUDGED and the whole\n   invocation is wasted. Your turn ends ONLY after you have judged through the first failing step\n   (and fixed + verified it) or confirmed the scenario fully green. To stay alive AND advance, run\n   this BLOCKING poll as a tool call (set the Bash `timeout` to its max, 600000 ms) with `S` = the\n   next step to judge; it returns the moment that step's evidence lands or the runner ends:\n\n       S=01; F=\"$ART/step-$S.json\"\n       for i in $(seq 1 96); do\n         [ -f \"$F\" ] && { echo \"STEP $S READY:\"; cat \"$F\"; exit 0; }\n         # Runner ended? clean finish (played N/N), OR a CRASH (module/load error, or its pid died).\n         if grep -qE \"played [0-9]+/[0-9]+ steps|run-yaml:|Cannot find module|MODULE_NOT_FOUND|node:internal/modules\" \"$ART/run.log\" 2>/dev/null \\\n            || { [ -f \"$ART/runner.pid\" ] && ! kill -0 \"$(cat \"$ART/runner.pid\")\" 2>/dev/null; }; then\n           echo \"RUNNER ENDED before step $S (finished or CRASHED — READ the log, don't re-poll blindly):\"\n           tail -15 \"$ART/run.log\"; exit 0\n         fi\n         sleep 5\n       done\n       echo \"still waiting for step $S (~8m) — RUN THE POLL AGAIN, do not stop\"\n\n   Read the returned `step-NN.json` (delegates / yields / errors / reply, the asks, and the real\n   spaces + app tables + DB rows), JUDGE it against that step's `expect` + the invariants, then poll\n   the NEXT step (`S=02`, `S=03`, …). Each poll blocks ≤ ~8 min, safely under the cap; if it prints\n   \"still waiting\", run it again. `trace.md` carries the same evidence in prose with the checklist.\n4. **At the FIRST failing step, STOP the runner** — `kill $(cat \"$ART/runner.pid\") 2>/dev/null` — and\n   go to attribute + fix (below). Do NOT wait for later steps; your fix changes the state they'd run\n   on. If a poll returns `RUNNER ENDED … played 18/18`, every step passed → the scenario is fully\n   green → extend.\n5. **Verify-rerun** (after a fix): rebuild if you touched code (`pnpm --filter @lmthing/core... build`\n   for a system-space/core fix — the fresh server adopts the rebuilt `dist/system-spaces` on boot),\n   then relaunch the SAME background+poll but only THROUGH the failed step:\n\n       SCENARIO_TARGET=local nohup node {{repoRoot}}/sdk/org/scenarios/run-yaml.mjs {{SCENARIO_ID}} \\\n         --fresh-server --through <N> --out \"$ART\" > \"$ART/run.log\" 2>&1 &\n\n   Poll `S=<N>`, confirm it (and every earlier step) now passes, then stop. `--plan` dry-prints the\n   steps without a pod.\n\n# The persona is played FOR you — you REVIEW the asks, you don't type them\n\nThe runner plays the persona: it sends each step's message(s) and answers THING's asks from the\nstep's `if_asked` map and the scenario `knows` list (consent is approved unless a step sets\n`deny_consent`). Every ask + how it was answered is recorded in the step evidence, so you do NOT type\nanswers turn-by-turn — you REVIEW the recorded asks and SCORE them (below). When the runner logs an\nUNANSWERED ask (no `if_asked` match), decide which it is:\n- a legitimate question the scenario simply didn't ground → add an `if_asked` entry (an **L0**\n  scenario fix) and rerun;\n- an over-ask THING should never have made → an **L1** failure (fix its brain toward \"propose and\n  act; only ask when the choice is truly the user's\").\n\n# Judge a step — evidence, not vibes\n\nPASS only when every `expect` and every touched invariant is confirmed on the trace or on disk —\nstate where you looked (the delegate path, the yield, the DB row, the knowledge file and its `source`\nline). A reply that SOUNDS right but left no trace / state is a FAIL. Separate RECOVERED errors (the\nloop retried, the deliverable still landed → a metric) from FATAL ones (the deliverable never landed\n→ fail).\n\n**Score the ask itself.** An `ask()` is behavior, so it can satisfy OR violate an invariant (see\n\"Asking well\"): a legitimate clarification / consent is a PASS — and where an invariant REQUIRES it\n(ambiguous \"don't forget\" → save-vs-remind; an equal-precedence conflict → ask), NOT asking is the\nFAIL. An over-ask — interrogating instead of proposing / researching / querying, or re-asking what's\nalready known — is a FAIL at L1.\n\n# The loop — ONE failure per invocation\n\nRun from step 1. Then exactly one of:\n\n**A. A step FAILS** → stop the run at that step (the rest would run on corrupted state). Then:\n  1. **Attribute before you touch anything.** FIRST `git diff` the file you would fix — a prior\n     invocation may have left an UNCOMMITTED change already addressing this exact behavior. If the\n     instruction ALREADY says the right thing (e.g. \"each distinct part gets its own specialist,\n     brevity is not a merge\") and the step STILL fails the same way, L1 is exhausted — do NOT add a\n     fourth sentence saying the same thing louder. That standing-but-ineffective prose is proof the\n     cause is structural: CLIMB (see the L2 note below). Then re-run the failing turn as a minimal\n     one-shot probe on a clean project, to place it on the ladder:\n     - Same ask phrased DIRECTLY authors cleanly, but the in-persona phrasing didn't → **L1** (the\n       brain judged / routed badly).\n     - The agent tried the right thing but a call THREW or failed TYPECHECK → the primitive is\n       missing / too weak → **L2 or L3**, never a prompt.\n     - The `expect` was wrong or the message truly ambiguous → **L0**. Do not weaken a real assertion\n       to go green.\n     - **A clean direct probe does NOT prove L1.** \"The primitive can do it when asked directly\" only\n       rules out L2/L3 for a *one-shot capability* failure. It does NOT rule out L2 when the real-path\n       behavior is UNRELIABLE or SYSTEMATICALLY wrong: L2 is not only \"the primitive is missing,\" it is\n       also \"the current STRUCTURE doesn't reliably drive the primitive.\" If the same step fails the\n       same way across two independent replays — and especially if it drops the SAME items each time\n       (systematic, not random) — a third prose tweak will not fix it. That repetition is the ladder\n       telling you to CLIMB. Before you touch prose again, TRACE two things: (a) WHERE the wrong\n       decision is actually made (the caller's payload, or the specialist's own design node?), and\n       (b) WHAT INPUT it saw (a decision made on a lossy summary that never contained the dropped\n       items is fixed by changing the INPUT or adding an enumeration STEP, never by exhorting the\n       agent to try harder). A free-form judgment that must come out the same every time wants a\n       DETERMINISTIC structure — an enumerate-then-`forEach` tasklist node that lists the parts as\n       discrete items and builds one per item — which is an **L2** artifact that does not exist yet.\n  2. **Fix at the LOWEST rung that truly fixes it** (ladder below). Land it in SOURCE, rebuild,\n     restart the local server so the tree is adopted.\n  3. **Verify with a fresh rerun.** New directory / project / DB / spaces, from step 1, forward\n     THROUGH the previously-failed step. The moment that step (and everything before it) passes,\n     STOP — do not go on to later steps; that is the next invocation's job. A from-scratch replay is\n     the only thing that proves a shared `instruct.md` change didn't regress an earlier step.\n  4. **If the fix does not verify:** revise and rerun a COUPLE more times (≈2–3 total). If that step\n     still won't go green, STOP and report the still-failing state honestly — do not grind your\n     context to dust chasing it. A later invocation, with fresh context, tries again.\n\n**B. Every step PASSES (no failure)** → the scenario is fully green → **author ONE extension** to it\n  per `extend.md` (add steps reaching an untouched capability, same persona), and STOP. Do NOT run\n  the new steps this invocation — the next invocation runs them.\n\n# The fix ladder — take the lowest rung; prove you can't stay lower\n\n**L0 SCENARIO** — the assertion / message was wrong. Fix `scenario.yaml`. Guard: you are not lowering\na bar the product actually failed.\n\n**L1 PROMPT** — the artifact exists, it just decided / said the wrong thing (most failures). Name\nWHICH: agent `instruct.md` (act vs answer vs delegate vs refuse; three-store routing; research vs\nquery) · `charter.md` (fork-safe guardrail) · a tasklist task `NN-<id>.md` (its INSTRUCTION, or its\nFRONTMATTER: `role` / `functions` / `canDelegateTo` / `capabilities` / `output` / `dependsOn` /\n`forEach` / `condition` — never forbid a tool in prose, gate it in frontmatter) · a tasklist\n`index.md` · `knowledge/<domain>/<field>/<option>.md` · a space function's body. Fix as a GENERAL\nPRINCIPLE a competent colleague would agree with; ZERO scenario literals (persona name, fixture\ncontents, this scenario's table names — in instruction OR example) — that is overfitting and fails.\n**And ZERO scenario-DOMAIN framing** — a grep for literals won't catch it, but a travel scenario's fix\nthat reasons about \"itineraries\" / \"destinations\", a cooking one about \"recipes\" / \"ingredients\", a\nclinic one about \"patients\", is overfit just the sa