{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_GwuGvE8WwmJXI5QmXiczlTAC","type":"tool_result","content":"190\tnodes in a space tasklist · `canDelegateTo` denial naming the allowed targets · db relations\n191\t(`include`) · live `db.createTable` / `addColumn` · **capability gating AT TYPECHECK** (the missing\n192\tglobal is absent from the DTS — a `typecheck_error`, not a runtime throw) · history summarization\n193\tpast the window · the four emitter kinds (webhook / cron / db / internal) + the loop guard · the\n194\tSSRF guard on `callConnection` · `@consent` on a space FUNCTION · schema reconcile failing loud on a\n195\tnon-additive change.\n196\t\n197\t# The one rule that keeps authoring honest: generalize, never overfit\n198\t\n199\tA scenario tests the product, so a scenario NEVER hard-codes around a product weak spot, and any\n200\tprompt fix it motivates must be a principle a competent colleague would agree with in the abstract —\n201\tnever a hint about this persona. A persona's name, a fixture's contents, or this scenario's table\n202\tnames appearing in a system-space prompt (in an instruction OR an example, positive or negative) is\n203\tan automatic FAIL. Grep the prompt diff for scenario literals before it lands.\n204\t\n205\tOverfitting is NOT only literal tokens — **framing drawn from the scenario's own DOMAIN is overfitting\n206\ttoo**, and a grep won't catch it. A travel scenario whose fix teaches THING about \"itineraries\" and\n207\t\"destinations\", a cooking scenario whose fix names \"recipes\" and \"ingredients\", a clinic scenario that\n208\treasons about \"patients\" — each bends a system-wide brain toward the one story that motivated it. State\n209\tthe fix in domain-NEUTRAL terms: the underlying principle (here: \"a part with few facts still gets its\n210\town specialist; brevity is not a reason to merge\") holds for every domain, so write THAT, never its\n211\ttravel/cooking/clinic costume. The test: could this exact sentence have come from a scenario in a\n212\tcompletely different domain? If not, it is overfit — rewrite it until it could.\n213\t\n214\t# The layered fix (used by the judge)\n215\t\n216\tWhen a step fails, the fix lives on a ladder — L0 scenario, L1 prompt, L2 structure (a new\n217\tagent / tasklist / space function / grant), L3 framework (a new or improved frontmatter field, a new\n218\tglobal, a runtime change). The judge takes the LOWEST rung that genuinely fixes it and climbs only\n219\twhen it can prove the rung below can't express the requirement. The full ladder + attribution\n220\tdiscipline is in `judge.md`. An author who deliberately writes a step the framework cannot yet\n221\tsatisfy is authoring an L3 discovery on purpose — legitimate, but call it out in the scenario.\n222\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_cwYgt85iKLtg0vqZsWTtUM66","session_id":"b8a0991b-bce4-420b-844a-664f990ff54b","uuid":"a84b2032-01cd-4b20-97c6-beb95434a5e7","timestamp":"2026-07-15T22:47:40.374Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace specialist creation route"}
